  "prompt": "How much is a sargeant's retirement if he was in the army for 30 years?",
  "response": "The retirement pay for an Army sergeant (or any military member) with 30 years of service is calculated using the **High-36 Retirement System**, which is based on the average of the highest 36 months of basic pay. For those who entered service **before September 8, 1980**, the **Final Pay System** may apply, but most current retirees fall under the High-36 system.\n\n### Key Factors:\n1. **Retirement Percentage**: 30 years of service equates to **75%** of the average of the highest 36 months of basic pay (2.5% per year \u00d7 30 years).\n2. **Basic Pay**: The exact amount depends on the sergeant's rank and years of service. For example:\n   - An **E-7 (Sergeant First Class)** with 30 years of service in 2023 has a monthly basic pay of **$6,763.50**.\n3. **Retirement Pay Calculation**:  \n   \\( \\text{Retirement Pay} = \\text{Average of Highest 36 Months of Basic Pay} \\times 75\\% \\)\n\nFor an E-7 with 30 years of service in 2023:\n\\( \\text{Retirement Pay} = \\$6,763.50 \\times 0.75 = \\$5,072.63 \\) per month (before taxes and deductions).\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- If the sergeant qualifies for **Cost-of-Living Adjustments (COLA)**, their retirement pay will increase over time to account for inflation.\n- **Bonuses, allowances (e.g., BAH, BAS)**, and other special pays are **not** included in the retirement calculation.\n\nFor an exact estimate, use the **DoD Retirement Calculator** or consult with a military finance office.",
